---
import "../styles/site.css"
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="vendor-subtree gives coding agents local upstream source without letting vendor code overwhelm your repository."
    />
    <title>vendor-subtree</title>
  </head>
  <body>
    <main class="landing-shell">
      <header class="landing-header" aria-label="Primary">
        <a class="brand" href="/">
          <span class="brand-mark" aria-hidden="true">v</span>
          <span>vendor-subtree</span>
        </a>
        <nav class="landing-nav">
          <a href="/docs/getting-started/">Install</a>
          <a href="/docs/strategies/">Strategies</a>
          <a href="/docs/doctor/">Doctor</a>
          <a class="cta cta-secondary" href="/docs/">Docs</a>
        </nav>
      </header>

      <section class="hero">
        <div class="hero-inner">
          <p class="eyebrow">Source vendoring for coding-agent repositories</p>
          <h1>vendor-subtree</h1>
          <p class="hero-copy">
            Put the exact upstream source your agents need inside the repo,
            keep it aligned with your dependency versions, and stop vendor code
            from drowning your editor, linters, diffs, and history.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a class="cta cta-primary" href="/docs/getting-started/">Start vendoring</a>
            <a class="cta cta-secondary" href="/docs/strategies/">Compare strategies</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <div class="signal-strip" aria-label="Product capabilities">
        <div class="signal">
          <strong>Subtree</strong>
          <span>Commit source when permanence matters.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="signal">
          <strong>Submodule</strong>
          <span>Pin big repos without copying their history.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="signal">
          <strong>Clone-ignore</strong>
          <span>Make source local for agents while Git stays lean.</span>
        </div>
        <div class="signal">
          <strong>Doctor</strong>
          <span>See detected stack, tools, editors, and vendor status.</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <section class="section">
        <p class="section-kicker">Why this exists</p>
        <h2>Agents work better when the real source is close.</h2>
        <p class="section-intro">
          Package docs are useful. The actual repository is better. `vendor-subtree`
          makes source available to coding agents and language tooling without
          turning every repo into an unreviewable mirror of the internet.
        </p>
        <div class="problem-grid">
          <article class="tile">
            <h3>Version drift is expensive</h3>
            <p>
              The tool can resolve versions from package manifests and lockfiles,
              then map those versions to source tags, branches, releases, or commits.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="tile">
            <h3>Vendor code should be visible</h3>
            <p>
              Agents and LSPs need to read upstream code, but review diffs,
              formatter runs, and lint passes should stay focused on your project.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="tile">
            <h3>One strategy is not enough</h3>
            <p>
              Small libraries can be subtrees, large repositories can be
              submodules, and temporary source mirrors can be clone-ignore entries.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <p class="section-kicker">The model</p>
        <h2>Choose the relationship you want with upstream source.</h2>
        <div class="strategy-grid">
          <article class="tile strategy">
            <h3>Subtree by default</h3>
            <p>
              Commit a copy under `vendor/` when the source is small enough and
              you want code review, history, and branch portability.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="tile strategy">
            <h3>Submodule when needed</h3>
            <p>
              Pin a repository without importing every file into your own history.
              Useful for large projects and upstreams you do not want to modify.
            </p>
          </article>
          <article class="tile strategy">
            <h3>Clone and ignore</h3>
            <p>
              Keep source on disk for agents and LSPs while `.gitignore` keeps it
              out of commits. This is also the fallback for colocated `jj` repos.
            </p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="section">
        <p class="section-kicker">Workflow</p>
        <h2>Discovery, vendoring, editor hygiene, and status in one loop.</h2>
        <div class="workflow-grid">
          <div class="terminal" aria-label="vendor-subtree command example">
            <div class="terminal-bar" aria-hidden="true">
              <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
              <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
              <span class="terminal-dot"></span>
            </div>
            <pre><code>$ vendor-subtree
<span class="ok">found</span> package.json, bun.lock, oxlint, Biome, VS Code
<span class="ok">resolved</span> effect@3.21.2 -> Effect-TS/effect#v3.21.2
<span class="warn">selected</span> strategy: subtree
<span class="ok">wrote</span> vendor/effect
<span class="ok">updated</span> .gitattributes, editor settings, agent notes

$ vendor-subtree doctor
<span class="ok">clean</span> 2 vendors synced, 4 tool surfaces configured</code></pre>
          </div>
          <article class="tile">
            <h3>Made for real repositories</h3>
            <ul class="check-list">
              <li>Detect package managers, monorepo tools, editors, and agent files.</li>
              <li>Apply ignores only for tools the project already uses.</li>
              <li>Support GitHub and other git hosts through provider layers.</li>
              <li>Keep dangerous history removal explicit and hard to run by accident.</li>
              <li>Expose a TUI for scanning, matching, and updating vendored dependencies.</li>
            </ul>
          </article>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="final-band">
        <div class="section">
          <p class="section-kicker">For agents and humans</p>
          <h2>Give the repo more context without giving it more chaos.</h2>
          <p class="section-intro">
            `vendor-subtree` turns upstream source into an intentional project
            surface: versioned, observable, editor-aware, and removable when it
            no longer belongs.
          </p>
          <div class="hero-actions">
            <a class="cta cta-primary" href="/docs/getting-started/">Read the docs</a>
            <a class="cta cta-secondary" href="/docs/cli-reference/">CLI reference</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <footer class="landing-footer">
        <span>vendor-subtree workspace</span>
        <span>Astro + Starlight docs for source vendoring workflows</span>
      </footer>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>
